AI-Powered Fake News Detector Highlights the technology powering it

Introduction:

The quick development of social media and digital media has significantly accelerated the dissemination of information, making it more challenging to seprate accurate news from inaccurate or deceptive content. In addition to mileading the public, fake news seriously jeopardizes social, political and economical stability. Conventional news verification techniques are frequently labor- intensive, manual, and inadequate to manage the huge number of daily news pieces. Therefore, intelligent system that can use cutting-edge computational approches to automaticlly and effectively identify fake news are desperately needed.

This project ensure the Natural-Language-Processing (NLP)the fake news detection platform. The system analyzes textual patterns, semantic context, and linguistic signals to differemiate between authentic and fradulant news stories by combinig methods like TF-IDF, word embeddings(Word2Vec/Glove), recurrent neural network(LSTM), and transformer based models (BERT). Accuracy and dependability are guranted by through exploratory data analysis (EDA), sophisticated preprocessing and stringent model evaluation, which makes this approch extremely useful for real world implementation in news verification system.

Business problem:

Fake News spread quickly in today's digital age, deceiving audiences, harming image, and influencing important choices in public health, politics, and economic. The vast amount of information makes it difficult for organizations and platform to manually check the legitmacy of material. An automated, intelligent system that can consistently identify and flag fake news is desperately neede to gurantee that users and those making choices have access to reliable and accurate information

Problem statement:

Public safety, informed decision-making, and societal trust are all seriously thrented by the pervasive spread of false information on digital platform. Current manual verification techniques are ineffective and cannot keep up with speed and amount of online content. The task is to create an automated, precise, and scalable system taht uses cutting-edge Natural Language Processting (NLP) and Machine Learning Technologies to analyze content, identify false ormisleading information, and distinguish it from authentic news in real-time

Datset link:-(https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/saurabhshahane/fake-news-classification

Objectives:

  1. Using cutting-edge Artificial intelligence (AI) and Machine Learning techniques, create a robotic fake news detection system that can reliably identify news article as authentic or fradulent.
  2. To identify Patterns, sementic context, and writing style distinctions between fake and authentic news, conduct through text analysis and feature engineering.
  3. To optimize classification performance, use cutting edge models like Transformers-based models (BERT), TF-IDF with logistic regression and LSTM Network.
  4. To guarantee dependability and equity, do through examination and validation utilizing a variety of measures as accuracy, precision, recall, f1 score, ROC-AUC, and Confusion matrix

PHASE 1 DATA ACQUISITION

The quality, quantity, and variety of the news data gathered directly affect the model's dependability and performance, making data collecting an essential first stage in the false news detection process. By using sizable and relastic datset, the system is gauranteed to learn authentic linguistic patterns of both fake and real news, improving the final model's accuracy, objecivity, and suitability for pratical application.

The foundation of the fake news detection system is made up of those libraries. Effective data processing, numerical calculation, and perceptive visualization are made possible by fundamental libraries like NumPy, Pandas, Matplotlab, and seaborn. Understanding news writing patterns requires advanced text preprocessing, linguistic analysis, sentiment recognition, and readability assessment, all of which are supported by NLP-focused tools like NLTK, spCy, TextBlob, and textstat. Libraries for feature engineering, such as Word2vec, n-gram, TF-IDF, assist in converting unstructured text into useful numerical representation. Classiacal, sequential, and tranformer-based model can be implementing using machine learning and deep learning framework (Scikit-learn, tenserflow, and Transformers). While evaluation and visualization libraries guarantee accurate model assessment, other tools like Levenshtein distance improve identification of altered or nearly identical information

Text cleaning function:

Im order to prepare raw text data from NLP tasks, the code defines a simple text preprocessing function. After making sure that the submission is a proper string, it uses BeautifulSoup to remove HTML tags, remove URL, and users regular expressions to remove emojis. After that, it eliminates unneeded speical character while keeping letetrs, numbers, and standarpunctuation. Lastly, it normalizes whitespace by eliminating superflous spaces. The end product is a clear, consistent text that can be used for additional modeling or analysis.

In[]:
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup

def basic_clean(text):
    if not isinstance(text, str):
        return ""

    # 1. Remove HTML tags
    text = BeautifulSoup(text, "html.parser").get_text()

    # 2. Remove URLs
    text = re.sub(r'http\S+|www\S+|https\S+', '', text)

    # 3. Remove Emojis
    emoji_pattern = re.compile(
        "["
        u"\U0001F600-\U0001F64F"
        u"\U0001F300-\U0001F5FF"
        u"\U0001F680-\U0001F6FF"
        u"\U0001F1E0-\U0001F1FF"
        "]+",
        flags=re.UNICODE
    )
    text = emoji_pattern.sub(r'', text)

    # 4. Remove special characters (keep letters, numbers, punctuation)
    text = re.sub(r"[^a-zA-Z0-9\s.,!?]", " ", text)

    # 5. Remove extra spaces
    text = re.sub(r"\s+", " ", text).strip()

    return text
In[]:
def tokenize_text(text):
    tokens = word_tokenize(text)
    return tokens
In[]:
stop_words = set(stopwords.words("english"))
def remove_stopwords(tokens):
    return [word for word in tokens if word.lower() not in stop_words]
In[]:
def preprocess_text(text):
    cleaned = basic_clean(text)
    tokens = tokenize_text(cleaned)
    tokens = remove_stopwords(tokens)
    return tokens

import spacy
nlp = spacy.load("en_core_web_sm", disable=["ner", "parser"])

This defines a function taht extracts basic textual prioperties, such as word count, character count, sentene count, and average word length, using spaCy and return the results as pandas series for additional analysis or modeling.

In[]:
def extract_features_spacy(text):
    if not isinstance(text, str):
        return pd.Series([0, 0, 0, 0])

    doc = nlp(text)

    words = [token.text for token in doc]
    word_count = len(words)
    char_count = len(text)

    # sentence count using spaCy's sentencizer (auto)
    try:
        sentence_count = len(list(doc.sents))
    except:
        sentence_count = 1

    # average word length
    if word_count > 0:
        avg_word_length = np.mean([len(w) for w in words])
    else:
        avg_word_length = 0

    return pd.Series([word_count, char_count, sentence_count, avg_word_length])

import squarify
from collections import Counter
from nltk.corpus import stopwords
# Ensure stopwords downloaded
nltk.download('stopwords')
stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))
# Function to get clean tokens
def get_tokens(text):
    tokens = re.findall(r'\b\w+\b', text.lower())
    tokens = [t for t in tokens if t not in stop_words and len(t) > 2]
    return tokens
# Extract fake news text only
fake_texts = df_sample[df_sample['label'] == 1]['cleaned_text'].astype(str)
# Flatten tokens
all_fake_tokens = []
for txt in fake_texts:
    all_fake_tokens.extend(get_tokens(txt))
# Count frequencies
fake_word_freq = Counter(all_fake_tokens).most_common(20)
# Prepare data for treemap
words = [w for w, c in fake_word_freq]
counts = [c for w, c in fake_word_freq]
# Treemap visualization
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 9))
squarify.plot(sizes=counts, label=words, alpha=0.85, text_kwargs={'fontsize': 12})
plt.title("Treemap of Top 20 Fake News Keywords", fontsize=20, fontweight='bold')
plt.axis('off')
plt.show()

Porter Stemming

The input text is tokenized using this function, which then applies the Porter Stemmer to each token. By reducing words to their root forms, stemming helps normalize word variance and shrinks vocabulary, both of which can enhance text cateorization model's effeciveness and performance.

In[]:
def porter_stem_text(text):
    tokens = nltk.word_tokenize(text)
    return [porter.stem(word) for word in tokens]

Snowball Stemming

This function applies the Snowball Stemmer to every word after tokenizing the enterd text. Snowball stemming helps enhance text normalization and feature quality for subsequent automatic language precessing tasx by reducing words to their most basic formns in more uniform and liguistic aware manner

In[]:
def snowball_stem_text(text):
    tokens = nltk.word_tokenize(text)
    return [snowball.stem(word) for word in tokens]

spaCy Lemmatization

Using spaCy, this function lemmatizes the input text by returning each word to its original dictionalry from while maintaining its meaning. By considering various word forms as the same, lemmatization reduces vocabulary size and enhances model comparision, making the text more appropriate for precise NLP analysis and modeling.

In[]:
def spacy_lemmatize(text):
    doc = nlp(text)
    return [token.lemma_ for token in doc]

3. POS Tagging

This code use spaCy to extract POS tags from cleaned text. The resultant dataframe ffers comprenhesive synthetics data that can be utilized as features in NLP models or for linguistic study

def get_pos_tags(text):
    doc = nlp(text)
    return [token.pos_ for token in doc]
from collections import Counter

def get_pos_counts(text):
    doc = nlp(text)
    pos_tags = [token.pos_ for token in doc]
    return Counter(pos_tags)

4. Named Entity Recognition (NER)

By using spaCy to extract named entites from cleaned text and classify them into specified classes (eg, PERSON, ORG, GPE, DATE). The generated dataframe allows for systematic analyisis of significant data in the text by storing each rext togeather with an index of discovered elements

In[]:
ENTITY_TYPES = [
    "PERSON",      # People names
    "ORG",         # Organizations
    "GPE",         # Countries, cities
    "LOC",         # Non-GPE locations
    "NORP",        # Political groups, religions, nationalities
    "EVENT",       # Elections, wars, attacks
    "PRODUCT",     # Weapons, gadgets
    "WORK_OF_ART", # Books, movies
    "LAW",         # Legal documents
    "DATE"         # Dates
]
def extract_named_entities(text):
    doc = nlp(text)

    # create dictionary with empty lists
    entities = {etype: [] for etype in ENTITY_TYPES}

    for ent in doc.ents:
        if ent.label_ in entities:
            entities[ent.label_].append(ent.text)

    return entities

PHASE 5 FEATURE ENGINEERING

1. TF-IDF Features (Unigram, Bigram, Trigram)

In order to transforms unstructured textual data into useful numerical representaions, this stage extract TF-IDF (Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency) features from cleaned text. To record single words, two-word phrases, and three word phrases, respectively, unigrams, bigrams, and trigrams are created. The model is guranteed to concentarte on most meaningful terms while maintaining computational efficiency by using capped feature size of 5,000. Each n-gram representation's dimensionality is verified by printing the featue matrix shapes.

Additionally it possible to see which words and phrase the TF-IDF model is emphasizing by looking at extracted feature names for Unigrams, bigrams, and trigrams. In addition to revealing significant patterns like commonly recuring terms and contextual word pairings, this gives the text data interpretability. In the detection of fake news, these TF-IDF feature provide a solid foundation for conventional machine learning models susch as LOgistic regression.

2. Word Embeddings:

Word Embeddings are used in this stage to capture the semantic meaning of the text's words. Each news story is first transformered into a series of tokens by tokenizing the cleaned text using NLTK into lowercase words. The tokenized format maintains the contextual order of words withinh each sentence and is neccessary for training embedding models.

3. Levenshtein V2

In this step, the degree of character similarity between successive news stories is measured using Levensthein similarity. It measures the amount of text that must be altered to change one article into another by calculating the normalized edit distance between the cleaned text of each article and the prior article. This feature aids in the identification of news content that is almost same, repeated, or barely altered. This is particularly helpful in the detection of fake news, as false information is frequently reused or slightly adjusted across several stories.

In[]:
!pip install python-Levenshtein
import Levenshtein
def levenshtein_similarity_v2(text1, text2):
    if not isinstance(text1, str) or not isinstance(text2, str):
        return 0.0

    dist = Levenshtein.distance(text1, text2)
    max_len = max(len(text1), len(text2))

    if max_len == 0:
        return 1.0

    return 1 - (dist / max_len)
df_sample["prev_text"] = df_sample["cleaned_text"].shift(1)

df_sample["levenshtein_similarity"] = df_sample.apply(
    lambda row: levenshtein_similarity_v2(row["cleaned_text"], row["prev_text"])
    if pd.notnull(row["prev_text"]) else None,
    axis=1
)

df_sample[["cleaned_text", "prev_text", "levenshtein_similarity"]].head()

Model 2 LSTM (Long Short-Term Memory)

In[]:
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Embedding, LSTM, Dense, Dropout
MAX_WORDS = 20000   # Vocabulary size
MAX_LEN   = 300     # Sequence length
EMBED_DIM = 128     # Embedding dimension

Build LSTM Model Architecture:

An LSTM- based deep learning model for detecting fake news is defined and assembeled this code. In order to capture sequential dependencies in the text, and LSTM layer with 128 int comes after an embedding layer that transforms input token into dense vectors. A dense layer with ReLU activation offers intermidate feature transformation, adn droput layer are added for regulization and overfitting reduction. The final output layer predicts binary label (Real or Fake) using sigmoid activition. the model's architecture summary gives a sigmoid acivation. The model's architecture summary gives summary of all layers and parameter, and its compile using Adam optimizer with binary cross-entropy loss.

In[]:
model_lstm = Sequential(name="FakeNews_LSTM_Model")
model_lstm.add(
    Embedding(
        input_dim=MAX_WORDS,
        output_dim=EMBED_DIM,
        input_length=MAX_LEN,
        name="Embedding_Layer"
    )
)
model_lstm.add(
    LSTM(
        units=128,
        return_sequences=False,
        name="LSTM_Layer"
    )
)
model_lstm.add(Dropout(0.3, name="Dropout_1"))

model_lstm.add(
    Dense(
        64,
        activation='relu',
        name="Dense_Layer"
    )
)
model_lstm.add(Dropout(0.3, name="Dropout_2"))
model_lstm.add(
    Dense(
        1,
        activation='sigmoid',
        name="Output_Layer"
    )
)
model_lstm.build(input_shape=(None, MAX_LEN))
model_lstm.compile(
    optimizer='adam',
    loss='binary_crossentropy',
    metrics=['accuracy']
)
model_lstm.summary()

    )

Create Torch Dataset

In[]:
class FakeNewsDataset(torch.utils.data.Dataset):
    def __init__(self, encodings, labels):
        self.encodings = encodings
        self.labels = labels

    def __getitem__(self, idx):
        item = {key: val[idx] for key, val in self.encodings.items()}
        item["labels"] = torch.tensor(self.labels[idx])
        return item

    def __len__(self):
        return len(self.labels)

train_dataset = FakeNewsDataset(train_encodings, y_train)
test_dataset  = FakeNewsDataset(test_encodings, y_test)

BERT Model Summary:

Provides a succinct overview of the model architecture by generating a summary of the BERT model's layers, including each layer's name, paramater shape, total number of parameters, and trainability.

In[]:
def bert_model_summary(model):
    rows = []
    for name, param in model.named_parameters():
        rows.append([
            name,
            tuple(param.shape),
            param.numel(),
            param.requires_grad
        ])
    return pd.DataFrame(
        rows,
        columns=["Layer Name", "Shape", "Param Count", "Trainable"]
    )

In[]:
def compute_metrics(pred):
    labels = pred.label_ids
    preds = np.argmax(pred.predictions, axis=1)

    precision, recall, f1, _ = precision_recall_fscore_support(
        labels, preds, average="binary"
    )
    acc = accuracy_score(labels, preds)

    return {
        "accuracy": acc,
        "precision": precision,
        "recall": recall,
        "f1": f1
    }
trainer = Trainer(
    model=model_bert,
    args=training_args,
    train_dataset=train_dataset,
    eval_dataset=test_dataset,
    compute_metrics=compute_metrics
)

ROC-AUC Score BERT Fake News Detection

In[]:
# Get raw predictions
pred_output = trainer.predict(test_dataset)
# Logits  probabilities using softmax
logits = pred_output.predictions
probs = np.exp(logits) / np.exp(logits).sum(axis=1, keepdims=True)
# Probability of "Fake" class (label = 1)
y_prob = probs[:, 1]
auc_score = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_prob)
print("ROC-AUC Score:", round(auc_score, 4))
fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_prob)
plt.figure(figsize=(6, 5))
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label=f"BERT (AUC = {auc_score:.3f})")
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], linestyle='--')
plt.xlabel("False Positive Rate")
plt.ylabel("True Positive Rate")
plt.title("ROC Curve  BERT Fake News Detection")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Conclusion Fake News Detection Project

Using cutting-edge NLP and machine learning techniques, this project effectively illustrates the end-to-end construction of a reliable fake news detection system. We discovered important patterns and traits that set fake news apart from legitimate news through thorough text preparation, feature engineering, and exploratory data analysis.

Logistic Regression (TF-IDF), LSTM, and BERT Transformer were the three models we applied and assessed. We found that transformer-based models, especially BERT, performed the best in terms of accuracy, precision, recall, and F1-score. The experiment demonstrates how deep learning and contextual embeddings are superior at identifying tiny semantic indicators that are frequently found in bogus news articles.

From a business standpoint, this method offers businesses, media platform, and fact-checkers pratical insight to effectively identify and reduce false information. In general the study highlights the signifiance of intergrating linguistic expertise, cutting-edge NLP methods, and contemporary AI models tom provide dependable, scalable solutions for the escalatinfg problem of fake news in digital media.
